Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Enterprise-wide capability to implement Zero Trust principles.
DEFINITION: Never trust, always verify. Continuous verification of all access requests.
KEY ASPECTS: • Identity-centric security • Least privilege access • Assume breach mentality • Continuous monitoring
BUSINESS VALUE: • Reduced breach impact (lateral movement prevented) • Improved compliance posture • Support for remote work and cloud • Lower total cost of ownership

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Identity as the new perimeter.
SCOPE: • User identity management • Service/workload identity • Device identity • Access governance
RESPONSIBILITIES: • Identity lifecycle • Access certification • Privileged access management • Just-in-time access

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Continuous risk assessment and mitigation.
INCLUDES: • Real-time risk scoring • Contextual risk evaluation • Anomaly detection • Threat intelligence integration

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Visibility across all trust boundaries.
COVERS: • Access pattern monitoring • Security event correlation • Compliance monitoring • Policy violation detection

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Protected access to all applications and services.
ENSURES: • Context-aware access • Multi-factor authentication • Conditional access policies • Session management

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
PRINCIPLE: Never trust, always verify.
MANDATES: • Every access request must be verified • No 'trusted network' assumption • Authentication required everywhere • Authorization checked continuously
RATIONALE: The perimeter has disappeared due to cloud, remote work, and SaaS. Traditional castle-and-moat security is obsolete.

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Users and services get minimum necessary access.
IMPLEMENTATION: • Default deny policy • Just-in-time access grants • Time-limited permissions • Regular access reviews

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Access decisions made continuously, not just at login.
MEANS: • Re-evaluate context constantly • Revoke access if risk increases • Adaptive authentication • Session monitoring

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
All data encrypted in transit and at rest.
SCOPE: • TLS 1.3 minimum for transit • AES-256 for data at rest • mTLS for service-to-service • No plaintext transmission

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Application components implementing Zero Trust:
CORE COMPONENTS: • PEP - Policy Enforcement Point • PDP - Policy Decision Point • PIP - Policy Information Point • IdP - Identity Provider
These are the building blocks of Zero Trust enforcement.

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
POLICY ENFORCEMENT POINT
ROLE: Enforces access decisions at the entry point.
RESPONSIBILITIES: • Intercepts all requests • Validates authentication tokens • Queries PDP for authorization • Enforces policy decisions (allow/deny) • Logs all access attempts
EXAMPLES: • Kong API Gateway • Nginx Plus • Azure API Management • AWS API Gateway
CRITICALITY: High - First line of enforcement

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
POLICY ENFORCEMENT POINT for East-West traffic
ROLE: Enforces policies for service-to-service communication.
CAPABILITIES: • mTLS enforcement • Service identity verification • Request authorization • Traffic encryption • Circuit breaking
EXAMPLES: • Istio Envoy Sidecar • Linkerd Proxy • Consul Connect

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
POLICY DECISION POINT
ROLE: Makes authorization decisions based on policies and context.
PROCESS: 1. Receives authorization request from PEP 2. Retrieves policy rules 3. Queries PIP for context (user, device, risk) 4. Evaluates policy against context 5. Returns decision (allow/deny + conditions)
EXAMPLES: • Open Policy Agent (OPA) • Azure Conditional Access • Axiomatics Policy Server • PlainID
KEY FEATURE: Centralized policy logic

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Service interface for authorization decisions.
API: • POST /authorize • Input: Subject, Resource, Action, Context • Output: Decision (Allow/Deny), Obligations
PERFORMANCE: • Response time: <50ms P95 • Throughput: 10,000 req/sec • Availability: 99.99%

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
POLICY INFORMATION POINT
ROLE: Provides contextual information for policy decisions.
CONTEXT ATTRIBUTES: • User attributes (role, department, location) • Device posture (compliance, encryption, patch level) • Risk score (anomaly detection, threat intel) • Environmental context (time, location, network) • Resource sensitivity (data classification)
DATA SOURCES: • HR systems • Device management (MDM/UEM) • Risk engine • Threat intelligence feeds

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
IDENTITY PROVIDER
ROLE: Authenticates users and issues identity tokens.
CAPABILITIES: • Multi-factor authentication (MFA) • Single sign-on (SSO) • Federation (SAML, OIDC) • Token issuance (JWT, SAML assertions) • Session management
EXAMPLES: • Microsoft Entra ID (Azure AD) • Okta • Keycloak • Auth0
ZERO TRUST ROLE: Identity is the new perimeter

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Multi-Factor Authentication enforcement.
FACTORS: • Something you know (password) • Something you have (authenticator app, hardware key) • Something you are (biometric)
METHODS: • TOTP (Time-based One-Time Password) • FIDO2 / WebAuthn • Push notifications • SMS (legacy, discouraged)

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
JSON Web Token containing identity and claims.
STRUCTURE: • Header: Algorithm, token type • Payload: Subject, issuer, expiration, claims • Signature: Cryptographic signature
CLAIMS: • sub: User ID • roles: User roles • groups: User groups • device_id: Device identifier • risk_score: Current risk level
LIFETIME: 1 hour (short-lived for security)

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Policy rules for access control.
FORMAT: ABAC (Attribute-Based Access Control)
EXAMPLE POLICY: ALLOW access to Customer_Data WHERE user.role = 'CSR' AND device.compliant = true AND risk.score < 50 AND time.hour IN [08:00-18:00]
POLICY ENGINE: OPA Rego, XACML, or custom

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Contextual attributes for policy decisions.
ATTRIBUTES: • user_id, roles, department • device_id, os, compliance_status • ip_address, geolocation, network • risk_score, anomaly_flags • resource_classification • timestamp, session_id

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Security Information and Event Management.
PURPOSE: Continuous monitoring and threat detection.
CAPABILITIES: • Log aggregation • Event correlation • Anomaly detection • Threat intelligence • Incident response
ZERO TRUST ROLE: Trust is continuously verified through monitoring

Column.name: Note

Demilitarized Zone - External-facing services.
TRUST LEVEL: Untrusted
CONTROLS: • All traffic inspected • No direct access to internal zones • Heavy monitoring • Rate limiting enforced

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Micro-segmented zone for application services.
TRUST LEVEL: Verified only
SEGMENTATION: • Network policies enforce isolation • mTLS required for all communication • No lateral movement allowed • Continuous monitoring

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Highly protected zone for data storage.
TRUST LEVEL: Highest security
ACCESS CONTROLS: • No direct access (only via data services) • All queries logged and audited • Encryption at rest enforced • Data masking applied

Column.name: Note
Column.value:
Isolated zone for administrative access.
TRUST LEVEL: High privilege, high scrutiny
REQUIREMENTS: • Privileged Access Workstation (PAW) • Just-in-time access • Session recording • Break-glass procedures

Column.name: Notes

PATTERN: Centralized authentication + conditional access
USE CASE: SaaS access, employee portals
FLOW: 1. User attempts access 2. Identity Provider authenticates 3. MFA enforced 4. Token issued with claims 5. Access granted through policy
BEST FOR: External user access, B2C scenarios

Column.name: Name
Column.value: Pattern B: API Zero Trust Pattern

Column.name: Notes
Column.value:
PATTERN: Secure service access via API Gateway
USE CASE: Digital platforms, B2B APIs
FLOW: 1. Consumer sends API request 2. API Gateway (PEP) intercepts 3. Gateway queries PDP for authorization 4. Request allowed or denied 5. Audit event logged to SIEM
BEST FOR: API-driven architectures, partner integrations

Column.name: Name
Column.value: Pattern C: Service Mesh Enforcement Pattern

Column.name: Notes
Column.value:
PATTERN: East-west microservice traffic control
USE CASE: Kubernetes environments, cloud-native architectures
FLOW: 1. Service A calls Service B 2. Sidecar Proxy intercepts 3. mTLS enforced (mutual authentication) 4. Policy checked continuously 5. Request allowed with encryption
BEST FOR: Microservices, zero trust within the cluster

Column.name: Name
Column.value: Pattern D: Data Access Control Pattern

Column.name: Notes
Column.value:
PATTERN: Sensitive data governed centrally
USE CASE: Banking data, healthcare systems
FLOW: 1. Application requests data 2. Data Access Service intercepts 3. Policy Engine validates context (user, purpose, sensitivity) 4. Masking or encryption applied 5. Filtered data returned
BEST FOR: Highly regulated data, PII protection
